.SH NAME
__nilfs_error \- report failure condition on a filesystem
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "void" __nilfs_error
.BI "(struct super_block *sb "  ","
.BI "const char *function "  ","
.BI "const char *fmt "  ","
.BI "... "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "sb" 12
-- undescribed --
.IP "function" 12
-- undescribed --
.IP "fmt" 12
-- undescribed --
.IP "..." 12
variable arguments
.SH "DESCRIPTION"

\fB__nilfs_error\fP sets an ERROR_FS flag on the superblock as well as
reporting an error message.  This function should be called when
NILFS detects incoherences or defects of meta data on disk.

This implements the body of \fBnilfs_error\fP macro.  Normally,
\fBnilfs_error\fP should be used.  As for sustainable errors such as a
single-shot I/O error, \fBnilfs_err\fP should be used instead.

Callers should not add a trailing newline since this will do it.
